05348nam a22006015i 9780773567382DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19991999xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735673827 a10.1515/97807735673822doi  a(DE-B1597)657334  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDT21.5bC58 1999eb 7aHIS0010002bisacsh04a960.3/21 aAli, Taisier M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCivil Wars in Africa :bRoots and Resolution /cRobert O. Matthews, Taisier M. Ali. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tForce as the Major Instrument of Resolution -- tManaging Political Change: Uganda under Museveni -- tLiberation Politics in Ethiopia and Eritrea -- tCivil War, the Peace Process, and Genocide in Rwanda -- tNegotiation as the Primary Instrument of Resolution -- tThe Civil War in Liberia -- tInside from the Outside? The Roots and Resolution of Mozambique’s Un/Civil War -- tProtracted Civil Wars -- tSomali Civil Wars -- tCivil War and Failed Peace Efforts in Sudan -- tCivil Wars Forestalled -- tLeadership, Participation, and Conflict Management: Zimbabwe and Tanzania -- tSecurity, Conflict, and Peace -- tRedefining “Security” after the Cold War: The oau, the un, and Conflict Management in Africa -- tConclusion: Conflict, Resolution, and Building Peace -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJohn Kiyaga-Nsubuga focuses on Yoweri Museveni and his National Resistance Movement regime's attempt to bring peace to Uganda. John Prendergast and Mark Duffield look at Ethiopia's long civil war and the role of liberation politics and external engagement. Bruce Jones studies the ethnic roots of the civil war in Rwanda. Elwood Dunn explores political manipulation and ethnic differences as causes of civil strife in Liberia. John Saul examines the role of Western powers in establishing peace in Mozambique. Hussein Adam describes the collapse of the authoritarian regime in Somalia and the subsequent rise of inter-clan and sub-clan rivalry. Taisier Ali and Robert Matthews argue that the forty-year conflict in Sudan is much more complex than the usual view that it results from the pitting of the Arab, Islamic North against the African, Christian South. Shifting the focus to how internal unrest may be managed, Hevina Dashwood examines government initiatives undertaken to maintain stability in Zimbabwe and Cranford Pratt describes the policies and institutions developed by Nyerere that enabled Tanzania to avoid ethnic, regional, and religious factionalism and intra-elite rivalries. James Busumtwi-Sam explores multilateral third-party intervention, highlighting the changing role of the OAU and the United Nations and their effectiveness in averting war. The concluding chapter draws together findings from the individual case studies and incorporates them into the larger corpus of the literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / Africa / General.2bisacsh1 aAdam, Hussein M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAli, Taisier M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBusumtwi-Sam, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDashwood, Hevina S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuffield, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunn, D. Elwood, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJONES, BRUCE D., econtributor.4